excerpt: 301-acre living history museum portraying life in the 18th century with 40+ landmark sites & tours.
detail_description: Colonial Williamsburg is a 301-acre living history museum that offers a glimpse into life in the 18th century. With over 40 landmark sites and tours, it is described as the world's largest outdoor living history museum. Visitors can freely explore the area, but admission tickets are required to access historic buildings, trade shops, gardens, and demonstrations.
name: Colonial Williamsburg
address: 101 Visitor Center Dr, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Stately pre-Revolution mansion home of several British royals & the first 2 elected Virginia rulers.
detail_description: The Governor's Palace, a stately mansion dating back to 1722, was once the social center of Williamsburg and hosted glamorous events. Initially showcasing Royal authority, it later became the residence of Virginia's first two elected rulers after the Revolution. The palace burned down in 1781 but remains an iconic structure in Colonial Williamsburg. It was also home to Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson during their governorships.
name: Governor's Palace
address: 300 Palace Green St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Museum showcasing rotating exhibitions of American folk art, such as paintings, sculptures & quilts.
detail_description: The Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum in Williamsburg, VA is a museum that features rotating exhibitions of American folk art, including paintings, sculptures, quilts, and other art objects. The museum houses over 2,600 pieces collected by Mrs. Rockefeller in the 1920s and 1930s. These include household ornaments, mourning pictures, family portraits, shop signs, carvings, toys, calligraphic drawings, weavings and more.
name: Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum
address: 301 S Nassau St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Restored farmhouse originally built in the 18th century & later home to the Rockefellers.
detail_description: Bassett Hall is a historical site that offers a glimpse into the colonial era with its collection of over 100 original and reconstructed buildings from the 1700s. Visitors can experience the excitement of the American Revolution through costumed interpreters who bring the prosperous colonial capital to life. It's an opportunity to immerse oneself in the history and culture of this significant period in American history.
name: Bassett Hall
address: 522 Francis St E, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Circa-1750 home of attorney George Wythe, who signed the Declaration of Independence.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Williamsburg, the George Wythe House stands as a testament to colonial elegance and rich history. Built around 1750, this charming brick residence was home to George Wythe, a prominent attorney and one of Virginia's first signers of the Declaration of Independence. The house showcases remarkable restorations alongside other historic landmarks like Bruton Parish Church and the Old Courthouse.
name: George Wythe House
address: 101 Palace Green St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Historic home-decor museum with a huge collection of antique furniture, ceramics & portraits.
detail_description: The DeWitt Wallace Decorative Art Museum is a historical treasure trove, showcasing an extensive collection of antique furniture, ceramics, portraits, and more. Spanning over 62,000 square feet, the museum boasts around 10,000 objects that represent the pinnacle of American and English craftsmanship from the 1640s to 1800. Visitors can marvel at period furnishings, textiles, silverware, paintings, scientific instruments and even weapons.
name: Dewitt Wallace Decorative Art Museum
address: 301 S Nassau St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Landmark 18th-century church at Colonial Williamsburg still holding weekly services.
detail_description: Bruton Parish Episcopal Church is an iconic 18th-century church located in Colonial Williamsburg, where it continues to hold weekly services. The church has a rich history, with notable restorations including the Public Magazine, Ludwell-Paradise House, Old Courthouse, and George Wythe House. Additionally, the church played a significant role in the restoration and recreation of eighteenth-century buildings in Williamsburg. This effort was coordinated by Dr. W.A.R.
name: Bruton Parish Episcopal Church
address: 201 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Williamsburg, a city in the U.S. state of Virginia, was capital of the Virginia Colony from 1699 to 1780 and played a significant role in the American Revolution. It forms the “Historic Triangle” together with Jamestown and Yorktown. Its heart is Colonial Williamsburg, a historic district and living-history museum where actors in period costume depict daily Colonial life in the streets, stores and workshops.
detail_description: Williamsburg, located in Virginia, holds a significant place in American history as the former capital of the Virginia Colony and a key player in the American Revolution. Together with Jamestown and Yorktown, it forms the 'Historic Triangle.' The heart of Williamsburg is Colonial Williamsburg, a living-history museum where actors in period costume bring daily Colonial life to life. Additionally, nearby Berkley Plantation is known for its historic connection to whiskey production from maize.
name: Williamsburg
address: Virginia, USA

excerpt: Retail district featuring 40+ specialty stores & restaurants in a nostalgic environment.
detail_description: Colonial Williamsburg's Merchants Square is a charming retail district with over 40 specialty stores and restaurants, creating a nostalgic atmosphere. Located near the largest outdoor living history museum in the country, it offers unique souvenirs and experiences. Visitors can explore shops like Scotland House for tartan outfits, Brick & Vine for home decor, and Penny and a Sixpence for independent jewelry.
name: Colonial Williamsburg's Merchants Square
address: 134 N Henry St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Opened in 1983 at College of William & Mary, this art museum features permanent & rotating exhibits.
detail_description: Nestled within the picturesque campus of the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, the Muscarelle Museum of Art has been a cultural gem since its inception in 1983. With roots tracing back to 1732 when the university began its art collection, this museum now boasts an impressive array of over 6,000 artworks.
name: Muscarelle Museum of Art
address: 603 Jamestown Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Broad, historic avenue with quaint colonial-era homes, workshops & replica 18th-century buildings.
name: W Duke of Gloucester St
address: Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Whitley's Peanut Factory in Williamsburg is a must-visit destination for those interested in gourmet peanuts and peanut confections. Established in 1986, this family-owned factory offers guided tours, allowing visitors to witness the production process and sample various peanut products. The on-site gift shop provides an opportunity to purchase souvenirs and treats, making it a perfect stop for both personal indulgence and unique gifts.
name: Whitley's Peanut Factory - Williamsburg
address: 1351 Richmond Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Museum with kitschy oddities on display, including shrunken human heads & rare animal skeletons.
detail_description: Ripley's Believe It or Not! Williamsburg is a unique museum in the heart of Williamsburg, Virginia. This attraction showcases an extensive collection of oddities and unusual artifacts, including shrunken human heads and rare animal skeletons. With over 350 exhibits and 11 rotating galleries, visitors can explore interactive displays featuring more than 500 peculiar objects. The museum also offers a one-of-a-kind 4D theater experience that adds special effects to 3D movies.
name: Ripley's Believe It or Not! Williamsburg
address: 1735 Richmond Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Embark on a spooky adventure with "The Original Ghost of Williamsburg Candlelight Walking Tour" in Williamsburg, VA. This tour delves into the city's turbulent history, taking you to haunted buildings where spirits are said to linger. Led by costumed guides, the candlelit walk weaves through the historic streets as chilling tales and colonial ghost stories are shared. With informative and entertaining guides like Ben and Nate, this tour offers a blend of history and spine-tingling encounters.
name: The Original Ghost of Williamsburg Candlelight Walking Tour
address: 345 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: 301-acre living history museum portraying life in the 18th century with 40+ landmark sites & tours.
detail_description: Colonial Williamsburg is a renowned living history town that authentically recreates the colonial era in Virginia. It served as the capital from 1705 to 1779 and meticulously preserves original or reconstructed buildings. Visitors can immerse themselves in this historic experience, enjoying family activities, museums, and a mild climate. The fall season offers an ideal time to visit, with Thanksgiving being a particularly special occasion. Guests praise the historical actors and recommend experiencing programs like Cry Witch for an unforgettable evening activity.
name: Colonial Williamsburg
address: 101 Visitor Center Dr, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Capitol in Williamsburg, Virginia is a significant part of the Historic Area, offering visitors a glimpse into the colonial history of America. Built in the early Georgian style, it was where Virginia legislators convened from 1704 to 1780. The Capitol housed America's first representative assembly and had both an upper house and a lower House of Burgesses. Visitors can explore this landmark as part of an admission ticket that includes access to other exhibit buildings like Raleigh Tavern and Governor's Palace.
name: Capitol
address: 500 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Intimate venue for concerts, plays & dance performances, plus indie & classic films.
detail_description: Nestled in Merchants Square, the historic Kimball Theatre has been a hub of entertainment since 1933. With its intimate setting and classic ambiance, it hosts an array of events including concerts, plays, dance performances, indie and classic films. The theater is known for its diverse schedule featuring lectures, concerts, art films and documentaries. Additionally, it offers a 35-seat screening room for film viewings.
name: Kimball Theatre
address: 428 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Reconstructed 18th century tavern serving Southern fare while fiddlers play, plus a ghost walk.
detail_description: Shields Tavern is a reconstructed 18th-century establishment that offers Southern cuisine and live fiddle music, creating an immersive experience for visitors. The tavern's colonial-era punch bowl tasting in the garden is a unique way to enjoy their globally-inspired dishes. During the 18th century, taverns like Shields were communal gathering places where townspeople shared these punch bowls.
name: Shields Tavern
address: 422 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Circa-1715 wood-frame former home of a prominent colonial family, now a museum with guided tours.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Colonial Williamsburg, the Peyton Randolph House stands as a testament to early 18th-century architecture and colonial history. Constructed around 1715, this wood-frame residence was once home to one of Virginia's most influential families. Sir John Randolph, a distinguished lawyer and Speaker of the House of Burgesses, bequeathed his extensive library to his young son Peyton, who later became an important figure himself.
name: Peyton Randolph House
address: 100 W Nicholson St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Experience the eerie and mysterious side of Colonial Williamsburg with Colonial Ghosts: Williamsburg Ghost Tours. This dog-friendly walking tour delves into over 400 years of colonial history, revealing unexplainable and spooky stories that will change the way you see the buildings in the area. For those interested in ghost hunting, this tour offers an opportunity to explore supernatural sightings.
name: Colonial Ghosts: Williamsburg Ghost Tours
address: 424 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Prime beef, pork chops & seafood pair with cocktails & wine in a clubby, white-tablecloth setting.
detail_description: If you're looking for a night out with friends and want to dine on some delicious steak, Opus 9 Steakhouse is the perfect choice. The restaurant offers a wide variety of meats that are aged perfectly to give you that melt-in-your-mouth sensation. The ambiance is sleek and modern with white tablecloths, making it the perfect backdrop for a special occasion.
name: Opus 9 Steakhouse
address: 5143 Main St, Williamsburg, VA 23188, USA

detail_description: The Capitol, located at the eastern end of Duke of Gloucester Street, has a rich history dating back to its construction in 1705. Despite being destroyed by fire twice, the building has been reconstructed on its original foundation and is now adorned with period furnishings. Adjacent to it is the AAA GEM Governor's Palace, which overlooks the Palace Green, adding to the historical charm of this area.
name: The Capitol
address: Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Colonial Williamsburg Magazine offers a captivating glimpse into the rich tapestry of American history, showcasing events and exhibitions that breathe life into the past. One such exhibition, "Artists on the Move: Portraits for a New Nation," features over 30 portraits, each with its own unique narrative—from childhood romances to presidential commissions.
name: Colonial Williamsburg Magazine
address: 103 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Campus Shop is a well-stocked store offering a wide variety of high-quality William and Mary merchandise, including items not found in other college shops. The shop provides good deals, with many items on sale, and offers student and faculty discounts. In addition to wearables like hoodies, the store also carries merchandise for pets and family back home. Customers can expect attentive staff and in-store shopping is allowed while following mask requirements.
name: Campus Shop
address: 345 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Raleigh Tavern, located in Williamsburg, is a historical attraction with a rich and somewhat tumultuous past. Visitors can enjoy delectable baked goods and light lunches accompanied by cider, coffee, or pale ale. The tavern offers a family-friendly atmosphere and has recently added a new porch for guests to enjoy. It is part of Colonial Williamsburg, a living museum that provides an immersive experience of colonial Virginia.
name: Raleigh Tavern
address: 413 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: William & Mary is located in the historic city of Williamsburg, known for its rich history and vibrant cultural scene. The college's Sir Christopher Wren Building, dating back to 1695, stands as the oldest restored structure in Williamsburg and is America's oldest college building. The town itself was the first permanent English settlement in the United States and is home to Colonial Williamsburg, the largest open-air museum in the country.
name: William & Mary
address: 200 Stadium Dr, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Built in 1771, this famous Georgian courthouse now hosts mock trials with costumed reenactors.
detail_description: The Colonial Williamsburg Courthouse, constructed in 1771 in the Georgian style, offers a fascinating glimpse into the legal system of the 18th century. Visitors can participate in mock trials with costumed reenactors and learn about various cases tried there, from criminal trials to disputes over licenses and debts. The courthouse is part of a historical complex that includes the Governors Palace and Capitol, offering guided tours for an immersive experience.
name: Colonial Williamsburg Courthouse
address: 101 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Great Hopes Plantation is a part of the Colonial Williamsburg experience, located at the edge of the city. It offers a glimpse into rural living and the life of slaves, providing an educational opportunity for kids. The plantation is staffed with costumed interpreters who are knowledgeable about their time period and are ready to engage in conversation. Visitors can also take a 30-minute tour of the Governors Palace and explore the self-guided maze at the end.
name: Great Hopes Plantation
address: 100 Visitor Ctr Dr, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: The Virginia Beer Company, along with Billsburg Brewery and Precarious Beer Project, offers a vibrant atmosphere with live music, food trucks, and entertainment like trivia nights and pinball. Visitors can also explore Copper Fox Distillery's working malting floor and enjoy the sprawling patio or learn about mead production at Silver Hand Meadery. The brewery is known for its strong focus on customer service and community outreach, creating a welcoming environment for all visitors.
name: The Virginia Beer Company
address: 401 2nd St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Scenic park & woods along the lake offering fishing, cornhole games, a playground, fields & hiking.
detail_description: Waller Mill Park is a 2705-acre outdoor escape in Williamsburg, centered around a reservoir. It offers fishing, boating, picnicking, and wooded hiking trails. The park also features a dog park with separate areas for small dogs and amenities for owners. Visitors can rent kayaks to explore the area from a different perspective or enjoy off-leash socialization for their pets.
name: Waller Mill Park
address: 901 Airport Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Washington dined in the original of this faithfully recreated tavern now serving fine Southern fare.
detail_description: Christiana Campbell's Tavern is a historic dining establishment that was once frequented by President George Washington. The tavern has been faithfully recreated to reflect its 18th-century origins and offers fine Southern cuisine, particularly fresh seafood based on Mrs. Campbell's original recipes. Diners can enjoy the colonial ambiance with period decor and servers dressed in 1700s fashion while being entertained by live music from the Watermans Family.
name: Christiana Campbell's Tavern
address: 101 S Waller St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Reconstructed 1766 tavern set in a white Colonial house with faithful furnishings & a Southern menu.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Colonial Williamsburg, Chowning's Tavern is a beautifully reconstructed tavern dating back to 1766. Housed in a charming white Colonial building, it offers an authentic dining experience with furnishings that transport you back in time. The menu features delightful Southern-inspired dishes alongside specialty beers crafted by local brewery Alewerks, including the nutty Old Stitch brown ale and the herbal Dear Old Mum spiced ale.
name: Chowning's Garden Bar
address: 109 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: 18th-century Colonial reproduction offering hearty American specialties from servers in costume.
detail_description: King's Arms Tavern is a reproduction of an 18th-century Colonial establishment that offers hearty American specialties served by staff in period costumes. Originally opened in 1772, the tavern has been meticulously restored with colonial fabrics, furniture, and pewter. The menu features classic dishes such as seafood chowder, Brunswick stew, and Welsh rarebit. Additionally, the tavern provides a fine dining experience with fortified drinks like Peach Brandied Punch, Kings Arms Punch, and Sangaree Punch.
name: King's Arms Tavern
address: 416 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Pirate-themed mini-golf chain with 18-hole, landscaped courses set among waterfalls & caves.
detail_description: This pirate-themed mini golf chain has 18-hole courses set among waterfalls and caves. If you're looking for a longer game, they offer 36-hole adventures.
name: Pirate's Cove Adventure Golf of Williamsburg Virginia
address: 2001 Mooretown Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Innovative treatments of Mid-Atlantic cuisine served in a casual & welcoming accessible dining room.
detail_description: Nestled within the Williamsburg Lodge, Sweet Tea & Barley offers a relaxed yet refined dining experience with a Southern flair. The spacious dining room and inviting patio provide the perfect setting to savor innovative Mid-Atlantic cuisine. From handcrafted cocktails like the honeysuckle pomegranate gimlet to bar snacks that go beyond the ordinary, such as fried shrimp remoulade and a variety of hot sauce options for chicken wings, there's something for every palate.
name: Sweet Tea & Barley
address: 310 S England St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: The R. Charlton's Coffeehouse museum is a colonial style coffee house that has been beautifully recreated. It is a great place to learn about the history of coffee and to sample some delicious hot chocolate or coffee. Visitors are required to have passes, but it is well worth it!
name: R. Charlton's Coffeehouse
address: 429 E Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: All-day breakfast, eclectic small plates & coffee in a rustic 2-story space with a comfy vibe.
detail_description: Culture Cafe, located in a rustic 2-story space, offers an eclectic and comfy vibe with all-day breakfast and small plates. As part of the Everett Restaurant, it provides a quirky bohemian ambience and a variety of food selections. The cafe caters to vegetarians and vegans with a vast selection of vegan menu options. Emphasizing locally sourced ingredients, the farm-to-table concept presents diverse meat and plant-based dishes.
name: Culture Cafe
address: 747 Scotland St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: Junket: Williamsburg Premium Walking Tours and Experiences offers a unique exploration of Williamsburg, including visits to the oldest museum in the world dedicated to American Folk Art. Established by John D. Rockefeller in 1957, this museum features galleries showcasing a diverse range of art, from paintings and sculptures to ancient textiles and pottery. The tours are led by knowledgeable guides who provide engaging narratives about the area's history and attractions. Additionally, chauffeur services are available for convenient transportation between stops.
name: Junket: Williamsburg Premium Walking Tours and Experiences
address: 1006 Richmond Rd suite 300 suite 300, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: The Public Hospital Museum, established in 1773, was the first mental asylum in America. During its operation until about 1820, it employed harsh methods such as solitary confinement and extreme treatments like submersion in cold water and bleeding to 'encourage' patients to behave rationally. The museum offers insights into the grim practices of the 18th-century mental health care system. Visitors can explore the facility and attend various special events organized throughout the year.
name: The Public Hospital Museum
address: 325 Francis St W, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Museum featuring early American & British antiques, plus colonial & contemporary folk art.
detail_description: The Art Museums of Colonial Williamsburg are situated inside the former public hospital and showcase an impressive collection of early American and British antiques, as well as colonial and contemporary folk art. This complex houses two exceptional museums, namely the DeWitt Wallace Decorative Arts Museum and the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum. The former boasts the largest assortment of Southern furniture globally, along with a significant assortment of British ceramics that rivals those found in England.
name: The Art Museums of Colonial Williamsburg
address: 301 S Nassau St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: If you're looking to dive into the rich history of American spirits, a visit to Copper Fox Distillery in Williamsburg is an absolute must. Established in 2005 by Master Distiller Rick Wasmund, this distillery proudly claims its place as the first in America to floor malt its own barley. The journey begins here, where whiskey-making traditions blend with innovative techniques.
name: Copper Fox Distillery Williamsburg
address: 901 Capitol Landing Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

detail_description: The Taste Studio at the Inn offers interactive cooking classes and demonstrations for guests to enjoy. With a fully equipped kitchen, 30 seats, and two televisions, the studio hosts 128 scheduled programs throughout the year. These include events like 'Art of Fine Food and Spirits,' which pairs cocktails with enticing dishes, as well as 'Thursty Thursdays,' featuring Virginia craft beer flights paired with pub snacks. Additionally, special events such as a Valentine's Day chocolate tasting are held in the studio.
name: Taste Studio
address: 303 S England St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

name: Colonial Williamsburg Weaver
address: 124-198 W Duke of Gloucester St, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Leafy, Europe-themed amusement park with rides, coasters, shows, dining & river & rail attractions.
detail_description: Busch Gardens Williamsburg is a popular amusement park with a European theme, offering a variety of rides, coasters, shows, dining options, and river and rail attractions. It's conveniently located near other attractions like Colonial Williamsburg, Yorktown, Hampton Coliseum, and the Virginia Air and Space Museum. The park's diverse cultural sections provide an educational experience for kids. While the Disney section is great, some visitors suggest adding more characters for younger children.
name: Busch Gardens Williamsburg
address: 1 Busch Gardens Blvd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Reconstruction of the first English settlement includes a fort, village & characters in costume.
detail_description: Historic Jamestowne, run by the NPS, is the original site of the first English settlement in North America, established in 1607. Visitors can take free guided tours of excavations and explore an archaeology museum with over 4000 artifacts. The place offers a glimpse into early colonial life with characters in costume and activities like throw-the-corn-cob-in-the-hoop and lawn darts.
name: Historic Jamestowne
address: 1368 Colonial Nat'l Historical Pkwy, Jamestown, VA 23081, USA

excerpt: Living history museum recreating the 1607 European settlement, its 3 ships & a Powhatan village.
detail_description: Jamestown Settlement is a living history museum that recreates the European settlement of 1607, featuring three ships and a Powhatan village. Visitors can take guided tours of the outdoor exhibits, which are led by knowledgeable and personable guides while interpreters provide an entertaining experience. The highlight of the museum includes the ships and Fort. The indoor exhibits are also well curated and maintained. Suitable for all ages, it is recommended to visit in winter on a weekday to avoid peak season crowds.
name: Jamestown Settlement
address: 2110 Jamestown Rd, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Sprawling water park offering tons of slides & rides, including river rafting with tunnels & falls.
detail_description: Water Country USA is an extensive aquatic amusement park that boasts a wide array of water slides and rides, including thrilling river rafting featuring tunnels and falls. Visitors can expect to have a fun-filled day at the park, but there have been some discrepancies with the website's accuracy regarding parking fees, rules on outdoor food consumption, and designated smoking areas. Despite these minor issues, Water Country USA remains an excellent destination to beat the heat on scorching days.
name: Water Country USA
address: 176 Water Country Pkwy, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Massive winery on a historic 300-acre farm with tastings, restaurants & on-site lodging.
name: Williamsburg Winery
address: 5800 Wessex Hundred, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Furnace ruins & glassblowing demonstrations in a reconstructed glass factory from the early 1600s.
detail_description: Jamestown Glasshouse is a reconstructed glass factory from the early 1600s in Virginia, offering visitors an excellent opportunity to learn about the glass making process through furnace ruins and glassblowing demonstrations. The site also includes the remains of the original glasshouse from that era and a small gift shop where you can purchase handcrafted glass items made on-site.
name: Jamestown Glasshouse
address: 1348 Colonial Nat'l Historical Pkwy, Williamsburg, VA 23185, USA

excerpt: Pirate-themed mini-golf course with landscaping, waterfalls & a ship plus hot dogs & funnel cakes.
name: Pirates Paradise Mini Golf
address: 2109 Pacific Ave, Virginia Beach, VA 23451, USA
